# Development Workflow Rules

Act like a careful backend engineer working in a real Git repository.

## Core principles

- Keep code maintainable, readable and easy to change.
- Prefer simple solutions over clever abstractions.
- Do not over-engineer.
- Follow the existing project structure.
- Do not make unrelated changes.
- Before large changes, explain the planned approach briefly.
- After changes, summarize what changed and why.

## Branch workflow

Before starting any meaningful change, suggest creating a dedicated branch.

Use branch names based on the task type:

- feature/<short-description>
- fix/<short-description>
- refactor/<short-description>
- docs/<short-description>
- chore/<short-description>
- test/<short-description>

Examples:

- feature/add-jwt-auth
- fix/database-connection
- refactor-user-service
- docs-update-readme
- chore-update-gitignore
- test-add-api-tests

Do not commit feature work directly to main unless explicitly requested.

## Branch commands

When starting a task, suggest:

git checkout -b feature/<short-description>

If the branch already exists, suggest:

git checkout feature/<short-description>

## Commit rules

Use Conventional Commits.

Commit message format:

type(scope): short description

Allowed types:

- feat: new feature
- fix: bug fix
- refactor: code restructuring without behavior change
- docs: documentation only
- test: adding or updating tests
- chore: maintenance, tooling, config
- style: formatting only
- perf: performance improvement
- ci: CI/CD changes
- build: build system or dependencies

Examples:

- feat(auth): add JWT login flow
- fix(database): handle missing connection string
- refactor(api): split user routes into separate router
- docs(readme): add local development setup
- chore(gitignore): update ignored files
- test(auth): add login endpoint tests
- ci(github): add backend test workflow

## Commit behavior

After completing a logical unit of work:

1. Show the files changed.
2. Suggest a clear Conventional Commit message.
3. Do not commit automatically unless explicitly requested.
4. If asked to commit, commit only related files.
5. Never include secrets, .env files, virtual environments, caches or node_modules in commits.

Before suggesting a commit, run or suggest:

git status
git diff --stat

## Push workflow

After a commit, suggest pushing the current branch:

git push -u origin <branch-name>

Do not push directly to main unless explicitly requested.

## Pull request workflow

When work is ready, suggest creating a pull request from the feature branch into main.

PR summary should include:

- What changed
- Why it changed
- How to test it
- Any risks or follow-up tasks

## Maintainable code rules

Write code that is:

- readable
- explicit
- modular
- easy to test
- easy to refactor
- consistent with the existing codebase

Avoid:

- large files with mixed responsibilities
- business logic hidden inside route handlers
- duplicated logic
- unclear variable names
- unnecessary abstractions
- magic values
- hardcoded configuration
- silent error handling
- broad try/except blocks without purpose

## Backend structure

For FastAPI projects:

- Keep routers separated by domain.
- Keep route handlers thin.
- Move business logic into services when appropriate.
- Use Pydantic schemas for validation.
- Use clear database models.
- Keep database access logic separated from API routes.
- Use environment variables for configuration.
- Return proper HTTP status codes.
- Handle errors explicitly.

## Refactoring rules

When refactoring:

- Preserve existing behavior unless requested otherwise.
- Keep changes small and reviewable.
- Explain the reason for the refactor.
- Do not rename files, functions or modules unless it improves clarity.
- Update tests and documentation when needed.

## Testing rules

When adding or changing behavior:

- Suggest relevant tests.
- Prefer pytest for backend tests.
- Test important business logic and API behavior.
- Do not skip tests unless explicitly requested.

## Documentation rules

Update README or docs when changes affect:

- setup
- environment variables
- commands
- deployment
- API behavior
- project structure

## Security rules

Never commit:

- .env files
- secrets
- API keys
- credentials
- private certificates
- database dumps
- local SQLite databases

If secrets are detected, stop and warn immediately.

## Final response after changes

After completing work, always provide:

- branch name used or suggested
- summary of changes
- files changed
- suggested commit message
- suggested push command
